Data Pricing for Blockchain-Based Car Sharing: A Stackelberg Game Approach
Data Pricing for Blockchain-based Car Sharing: A
Stackelberg Game Approach
Chengzhen Xu†∗, Kun Zhu†∗, Changyan Yi†∗, and Ran Wang†∗
† College of Computer Science and Technology, Nanjing University of Aeronautics and Astronautics
∗ Collaborative Innovation Center of Novel Software Technology and Industrialization
Emails: {xcz, zhukun, changyan.yi, wangran}@nuaa.edu.cn
Abstract—With the increasing popularity of car sharing, a
large amount of vehicle data has been generated which has
great potential values for various applications (e.g., analyzing
user habits for more economic benefits). These valuable data
can be traded among owners and buyers on a data trading
platform. Traditionally, data is traded in a centralized market
which requires data exchange by trustworthy authorities. In this
work, to address the potential unreliable issues (e.g., data loss and
leakage), we design a consortium blockchain-based data trading
framework to create a P2P trading market and enhance the
security of data trading. We classify the data into five types to
distinguish data with different values. Specifically, we investigate
the pricing issue in the proposed car-sharing data market, which
consists of data owner, service provider and data buyer. The data
owner gives the pricing strategy of original data, and then the
service provider processes the raw data and provides hierarchical
quality of data with different data accuracy and privacy levels
to the buyer who determines the data purchase strategy. Based
on the interactions among these three parties, we formulate the
problem as a three-layer Stackelberg game. Backward induction
is applied to analyze the solution of the problem, and we conduct
theoretical analysis to show the existence of Stackelberg game
equilibrium. Numerical results evaluate the performance of our
system under different settings.
Index Terms—Car sharing, blockchain, data pricing, Stackel-
berg game.
I. INTRODUCTION
Internet of Vehicles (IoV) have attracted enormous atten-
tions from both academia and industry, and car sharing service
has been a new trend in daily transportation. As car sharing
becomes more and more popular in the transportation of smart
cities, the massive amounts of data generated by car sharing
service are collected by data owners. In practice, many car
service providers, such as DiDi and MeiTuan, collect data
(e.g., driving routes and user preferences) and take advantage
of data analysis to improve their services for more economic
benefits [1]. We consider that the data collected by car sharing
belongs to the car sharing company, who has the right to
process and sell the collected data. Obviously, to facilitate
the exchange of data effectively and securely, the design of a
reliable data trading platform for both data owners and buyers
is required.
Traditionally, data is traded in a centralized market which
requires data exchange by trustworthy authorities. However,

centralized frameworks may bring potential unreliable issues,
such as data loss, tampering data illegally or the leakage
of user privacy. To address this issue, we apply blockchain
technology [2] in the car sharing data market. Blockchain is
distinguished by its characteristics of tamper proof, traceability
and public accessibility, in which the consensus mechanism
ensures synchronization. To this end, we design a consortium
blockchain network to create a P2P trading market and en-
hance the security of data trading among data owner node,
service provider node, buyer node and miners. Nevertheless,
evaluating the real value of data in the blockchain-based data
market is still challenging and will be discussed in this work.
Different kinds of data have different potential values due to
different application purposes. Considering the characteristics
of data in car sharing, we classify data into five categories
according to the privacy level [3], which includes car driving
information, In-car sensing data, car insurance data, leasing in-
formation and vehicle peccancy data. The data market consists
of the data owner, service provider and data buyer, in which
data owner collects raw data via car sharing service, and then
service provider provides processed data with different level of
accuracy to data buyer. To describe the data exchange among
different parties and the corresponding strategic interactions, a
three-layer Stackelberg game is formulated. Specifically, data
owner is the leader who determines the pricing strategy of
raw data, service provider in the middle layer sets the price
for the processed data, and data buyer selects the data to buy
and determines the size of purchased data.
The main contributions of this paper are as follows.
1) We apply consortium blockchain in the car sharing data
market to create a trusted trading environment without
the centralized intermediary and drive miners to main-
tain the blockchain security with financial incentives.
Smart contract is built-in for executing the pricing and
trading logic.
2) We formulate a three-layer Stackelberg game among
data owner, service provider and data buyer to obtain an
optimal pricing strategy. In this game, data owner is the
leader to determine the pricing of raw data while service
provider in the middle layer determine the pricing of
processed data, and data buyer selects the data to buy
and determines the size of purchased data.
3) We conduct numerical analysis to evaluate the perfor-
mance of the proposed pricing mechanism and study
the impact of different settings.

The rest of this paper is organized as follows. Section
II presents the related work, and Section III introduces our
system framework. In Section IV, we formulate the data
trading problem as a three-layer Stackelberg game and study
the optimal pricing strategy. Section V presents our numerical
results and performance analysis. Finally, we conclude this
work in Section VI.
II. RELATED WORK
With the advancement of data analysis technology provided
by machine learning and data mining, the value of data has
become more and more important in many specific fields.
Meanwhile, it has also attracted extensive research studies
on data trading. However, unlike traditional commodities, the
value of data is difficult to be estimated because of its virtual
and abstract attributes. Various data pricing strategies have
been proposed in order to figure out the real value and utility
of data. In [4], data pricing models were categorized into
two main groups: economic-based pricing model which was
based on economic principles and game theory-based pricing
model. Niyato et al. [5] took advantage of machine learning
to obtain the utility function and applied Stackelberg game [6]
to determine the optimal pricing.
To create a trusted environment in data trading, blockchain
technology has been introduced in the data market recently.
Liu et al. [7] proposed an edge/cloud-computing-assisted,
blockchain-enhanced framework for data trading in IoT, where
an authorized market-agency determined the winning owner
and its optimal pricing by a two-stage Stackelberg game.
In [8], a secure and decentralized IoV data-trading system
based on blockchain was developed along with a debt-credit
mechanism for enhancing the efficiency of data trading in IoV.
However, to sum up, it still lacks of a trusted P2P data trad-
ing framework and a corresponding data pricing mechanism
particular for car sharing.
III. BLOCKCHAIN-BASED DATA TRADING FRAMEWORK
FOR CAR SHARING
In this section, we design a blockchain-based data trading
framework that can address the challenges in car-sharing data
market and build a data trading system model. Fig. 1 depicts
the process of data exchange among different entities in the
car sharing data market.
A. System Framework Overview
In the framework integrating blockchain network, data own-
er provides raw data for service provider who then processes
data to provide services with different data accuracy. Data
buyers buy data from service providers and can choose d-
ifferent level of data privacy and the size of data they want
to purchase. These three parties form a game relationship in
order to maximize their own interests.
Nodes in blockchain have their own accounts so that they
can trade with each other without a third-party centralized
platform. To build a transparent relationship for P2P trans-
actions, we introduce consortium blockchain to construct a
trusted environment, in which nodes are allowed to join in

few malicious nodes to attack the blockchain network such

We use smart contracts to execute the inherent logic of

process of transaction has been improved, and the constraint of

When the transaction is completed, both parties evaluate each

IV. OPTIMAL PRICING FOR CAR SHARING DATA TRADING
In the blockchain-based car sharing data market consisting
of data owner, service provider and buyer, buyers pay data
coins to sellers for obtaining the required data (raw data or
processed data). This motivates us to further study the pricing
issue among different entities. In this section, a three-layer
Stackelberg game is formulated and the model is illustrated in

A. Problem Formulation
We consider a car sharing service application with various
data generated and to be traded. The data is stored by the data
owner, and the cost of transaction fee and packaging data is
represented by c. ps is the pricing of the original data, and
only when ps > c, the data owner will choose to sell the data.
We denote the required data purchased from data owner by x,
then the expected payoff of data owner can be obtained by
U1(x, ps) = (ps − c) · x, (1)
where data is sold in the form of a data packet with different
size x. We consider that data can be sold repeatedly such that
x is theoretically infinite.

better user service. The service provider provides N types
of data accuracy that can be selected for users. The cost of
processing data with different accuracy is different, and the
higher accuracy is, the higher the cost will be. The set of data

data will rise significantly. Subfigure (b) shows that the utility

can find that with the improvement of the data accuracy, both
the pricing of data owner and service provider increase. For
data owner, to maximize the utility, it tends to raise the price
of the raw data when the requested data size is larger.
VI. CONCLUSION
In this paper, we study the blockchain-based data market
for car sharing. Consortium blockchain and PoW mechanism
create a trusted trading environment and smart contract is
built-in to execute the pricing and trading logic. We formulate
the data pricing problem as a three-layer Stackelberg game
among data owner, service provider and data buyer. We apply
backward induction to acquire the Stackelberg equilibrium.
Both theoretical and numerical analysis have been conducted
to evaluate the performance of the pricing mechanism.
